nial Tunis or the popular historical novels published in Istanbul and Cairo from the late nineteenth century onward. Several of the contributors focus on European culture as a repository of harem representations, but most of them tackle indigenous representations of home spaces and their significance for how the bodies of men and women, and girls and boys, were distributed in social space, from early Islamic Mecca to early-twentieth-century Cairo.Contributors. Asma Afsaruddin, Orit Bashkin, Marilyn Booth, Nadia Maria El Cheikh, Julia Clancy-Smith, Joan DelPlato, Jateen Lad, Nancy Micklewright, Yaseen Noorani, Leslie Peirce, Irvin Cemil Schick, A. Holly Schissler, Heghnar Zeitlian Watenpaugh  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aHarems. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh1 aAfsaruddin, Asma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAfsaruddin, Asma.1 aBashkin, Orit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBooth, Marilyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBooth, Marilyn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aClancy-Smith, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelPlato, Joan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEl Cheikh, Nadia Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEl Cheikh, Nadia Maria.1 aLad, Jateen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMicklewright, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoorani, Yaseen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoorani, Yaseen.1 aPeirce, Leslie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchick, Irvin Cemil.1 aSchick, İrvin Cemil, econtrib